<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-831-652  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 831 652.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  July 30 1990 v4 n28 p38(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Firm builds custom atomic patterns in glass.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Isotec Limited Partnership, an Arizona-based materials scienceresearch company, announces a process for building custom atomicpatterns in glass.andP;  The process improves lenses for imagingsystems and boosts the capacity of fiber optic cables.andO;Previously, glass had to be crushed into a lens for opticalfunctions.andP;  Isotec has simplified the whole process by arrangingthe atoms of the glass into specific patterns.andP;  The customdesigned atomic structures are then capable of directing lightbeams to satisfy customer specifications.andP;  This invention couldhave an impact on the technology of optical computing in whichphotons generating minimum heat and lacking mass could substituteelectrons in integrated circuits.andP;  The federal government isalready showing interest in this new technology.andP;  Isotec has sofar been contacted by the Army's night vision research group todiscuss the use of this science for night vision military goggles.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   ISOTEC L.P. (research).andO;Topic:     TechnologyImage EnhancementHigh ResolutionComputer VisionFiber OpticsManufacturingNew Technique.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>